(7013, 7, 7010, NULL, 1, 'The Great Silence: Leading Theories', 'Leading Theories is filed as a secondary codex heading under The Great Silence and serves as a practical briefing layer for commanders, diplomats, and investigators. The current synthesis ties the topic to Great Silence and Keth''Sa Incident, while historical context from the The Breach clarifies why policy language remains deliberately conservative. Analysts emphasize that this subtopic cannot be read apart from infrastructure strain, legal jurisdiction boundaries, and the uneven administrative capacity of member worlds. Independent Arbiter assessments routinely classify local governance quality as the deciding factor in long-term recovery. Recent audits found that outcomes improve when local actors share telemetry early, standardize terminology, and publish cross-species compatibility guidance before incidents escalate. In training doctrine, leading theories is used as a case study for balancing speed and restraint under uncertain intelligence conditions. Planners therefore rank the domain as high consequence even when incident frequency appears low in public summaries.', NULL, NULL, 3);

