(10040, 10, NULL, 2, 0, 'Veil Expanse Incidents', 'Veil Expanse Incidents is catalogued by the Veil Compact Codex as a core the hollow reference topic and is maintained by analysts on the Spire for active policy use. Current briefs link Veil Expanse Incidents to Veil Expanse sightings, classified telemetry, and pattern recursion, with recurring relevance to kilometre-scale hulls across both frontier and core systems. In post-Breach doctrine, the subject is no longer treated as static background lore but as an operational variable that shapes Accord readiness, diplomatic posture, and civilian confidence. Cross-species standards now require explicit compatibility notes for dextro and levo biochemistry in all deployed systems. Comparative reviews from 2698 PF to 2740 PF show that decision quality improves when planners evaluate technical limits, legal mandates, and cultural memory together rather than in isolation. Records from Arbiter debriefs and Directorate archives repeatedly highlight spillover effects into trade, migration, and recruitment pipelines whenever this domain is mishandled. The Accord Council treats the subject as strategically sensitive and updates advisories quarterly from the Spire. This is why Accord briefings separate tactical confidence from strategic confidence and prohibit collapsing the two metrics.', 150040, 100040, 5);

INSERT INTO codex_entries
    (id, category_id, parent_entry_id, requirement_id, entry_type, title, content, audio_id, image_id, sort_order)
VALUES
(10041, 10, 10040, 2, 1, 'Veil Expanse Incidents: Post-Breach Sightings', 'Post-Breach Sightings is filed as a secondary codex heading under Veil Expanse Incidents and serves as a practical briefing layer for commanders, diplomats, and investigators. The current synthesis ties the topic to Veil Expanse sightings and Great Silence correlations, while historical context from the counter-Hollow doctrine clarifies why policy language remains deliberately conservative. Analysts emphasize that this subtopic cannot be read apart from infrastructure strain, legal jurisdiction boundaries, and the uneven administrative capacity of member worlds. Reclamation teams continue to cross-reference Architect-era fragments with modern telemetry to close persistent evidentiary gaps. Recent audits found that outcomes improve when local actors share telemetry early, standardize terminology, and publish cross-species compatibility guidance before incidents escalate. In training doctrine, post-breach sightings is used as a case study for balancing speed and restraint under uncertain intelligence conditions. As a result, most command schools teach conservative escalation ladders with mandatory civilian-harm checkpoints.', NULL, NULL, 1),
(10042, 10, 10040, 2, 1, 'Veil Expanse Incidents: The Suppressed Report', 'The Suppressed Report is filed as a secondary codex heading under Veil Expanse Incidents and serves as a practical briefing layer for commanders, diplomats, and investigators. The current synthesis ties the topic to Veil Expanse sightings and Great Silence correlations, while historical context from the counter-Hollow doctrine clarifies why policy language remains deliberately conservative. Analysts emphasize that this subtopic cannot be read apart from infrastructure strain, legal jurisdiction boundaries, and the uneven administrative capacity of member worlds. Public education editions remove casualty imagery, yet service editions retain full after-action appendices for training. Recent audits found that outcomes improve when local actors share telemetry early, standardize terminology, and publish cross-species compatibility guidance before incidents escalate. In training doctrine, the suppressed report is used as a case study for balancing speed and restraint under uncertain intelligence conditions. Planners therefore rank the domain as high consequence even when incident frequency appears low in public summaries.', NULL, NULL, 2),
(10043, 10, 10040, 2, 1, 'Veil Expanse Incidents: Current Monitoring', 'Current Monitoring is filed as a secondary codex heading under Veil Expanse Incidents and serves as a practical briefing layer for commanders, diplomats, and investigators. The current synthesis ties the topic to Veil Expanse sightings and Great Silence correlations, while historical context from the counter-Hollow doctrine clarifies why policy language remains deliberately conservative. Analysts emphasize that this subtopic cannot be read apart from infrastructure strain, legal jurisdiction boundaries, and the uneven administrative capacity of member worlds. Independent Arbiter assessments routinely classify local governance quality as the deciding factor in long-term recovery. Recent audits found that outcomes improve when local actors share telemetry early, standardize terminology, and publish cross-species compatibility guidance before incidents escalate. In training doctrine, current monitoring is used as a case study for balancing speed and restraint under uncertain intelligence conditions. As a result, most command schools teach conservative escalation ladders with mandatory civilian-harm checkpoints.', NULL, NULL, 3);

